This lesson will go into the process of creating checkboxes for your form.
Those questions which might require more than one answer? yeah for those questions.

Checkboxes are also a type of 'input'
Nested within their own <label> element like radio buttons
Follows the same principles of radio buttons actually where wrapping an <input> element inside of a <label> element
it will automatically associate the checkbox 'input' with the <label> element surrounding it.

All related checkbox inputs should have the same 'name' attribute.
It is considered best practice to explicitly define the relationship between a checkbox input and its corresponding 
label by setting the 'for' attribute on the <label> element to match the 'id' attribute of the associated input element.

The example provided by FCC:
<label for="loving"><input id="loving" type="checkbox" name="personality"> Loving</label>

The intial code:
<h2>CatPhotoApp</h2>
<main>
  <p>Click here to view more <a href="#">cat photos</a>.</p>

  <a href="#"><img src="https://bit.ly/fcc-relaxing-cat" alt="A cute orange cat lying on its back."></a>

  <p>Things cats love:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>cat nip</li>
    <li>laser pointers</li>
    <li>lasagna</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Top 3 things cats hate:</p>
  <ol>
    <li>flea treatment</li>
    <li>thunder</li>
    <li>other cats</li>
  </ol>
  <form action="/submit-cat-photo">
    <label for="indoor"><input id="indoor" type="radio" name="indoor-outdoor"> Indoor</label>
    <label for="outdoor"><input id="outdoor" type="radio" name="indoor-outdoor"> Outdoor</label><br>
    <input type="text" placeholder="cat photo URL" required>
    <button type="submit">Submit</button>
  </form>
</main>

The task required me to add a set of three checkboxes to the form and should have each one nested within its own <label>
element.
All three should share the 'name' attribute of "personality"

The was my code:
<h2>CatPhotoApp</h2>
<main>
  <p>Click here to view more <a href="#">cat photos</a>.</p>

  <a href="#"><img src="https://bit.ly/fcc-relaxing-cat" alt="A cute orange cat lying on its back."></a>

  <p>Things cats love:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>cat nip</li>
    <li>laser pointers</li>
    <li>lasagna</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Top 3 things cats hate:</p>
  <ol>
    <li>flea treatment</li>
    <li>thunder</li>
    <li>other cats</li>
  </ol>
  <form action="/submit-cat-photo">
    <label for="indoor"><input id="indoor" type="radio" name="indoor-outdoor"> Indoor</label>
    <label for="outdoor"><input id="outdoor" type="radio" name="indoor-outdoor"> Outdoor</label><br>
    <input type="text" placeholder="cat photo URL" required>
    <button type="submit">Submit</button>
    <label for="Love"><input id="Love" type="checkbox" name="personality"> Love</label>
    <label for="Hate"><input id="Hate" type="checkbox" name="personality"> Hate</label>
    <label for="Jealous"><input id="lJealous" type="checkbox" name="personality"> Jealous</label>
  </form>
</main>

REMEMBER to add these checkboxes WITHIN your form element
As you can see, each checkbox follows the principles spoken about above.
All three checboxes have the 'name' attribute of "personality" as well which the name of their group.
Again, fiddling around with these attributes will give you different output so give it a go
